00:16:24.294 --> 00:16:25.270
OK.

00:16:25.270 --> 00:16:27.080
Enough enjoyment and
fun and games.

00:16:27.080 --> 00:16:31.070
Let's get serious, back down to
what we were doing earlier.

00:16:31.070 --> 00:16:35.320
We had established in earlier
discussion that there are a

00:16:35.320 --> 00:16:43.800
very limited number of ways in
which we can arrange a mirror

00:16:43.800 --> 00:16:46.040
plane and a rotation
axis about one

00:16:46.040 --> 00:16:47.690
fixed point in space.

00:16:47.690 --> 00:16:51.440
And these, accordingly, are
called the point groups.

00:16:51.440 --> 00:16:54.640
And in particular, they are
the two-dimensional

00:16:54.640 --> 00:16:56.215
crystallographic point groups.

00:17:03.100 --> 00:17:08.859
We had rotation axes by
themselves, 1, 2, 3, 4, and 6.

00:17:08.859 --> 00:17:11.730
And these are the only ones we
need worry about because these

00:17:11.730 --> 00:17:14.720
are the only rotational
symmetries that are compatible

00:17:14.720 --> 00:17:16.369
with translation.

00:17:16.369 --> 00:17:17.679
Then we had a mirror plane.

00:17:20.790 --> 00:17:24.240
And then there was no reason
why we could not combine a

00:17:24.240 --> 00:17:27.319
mirror plane with these
rotational symmetries.

00:17:27.319 --> 00:17:31.500
And in doing so, we used a
theorem that said if you take

00:17:31.500 --> 00:17:35.590
two reflection operations,
sigma 1 and sigma 2-- and

00:17:35.590 --> 00:17:38.510
again, I use sigma to represent
an individual

00:17:38.510 --> 00:17:41.350
operation of reflection--

00:17:41.350 --> 00:17:45.540
and a mirror plane is the
locus of operations of

00:17:45.540 --> 00:17:47.415
reflection, and then reflecting
back again, there

00:17:47.415 --> 00:17:49.200
are two operations involved.

00:17:49.200 --> 00:17:53.920
And if these are combined at
some angle mu, sigma 1

00:17:53.920 --> 00:17:58.480
followed by sigma 2, when they
are separated by an angle mu

00:17:58.480 --> 00:18:02.940
is the same as the net
transformation of a rotation

00:18:02.940 --> 00:18:06.300
about their point of
intersection through twice the

00:18:06.300 --> 00:18:09.780
angle which the mirror
planes are combined.

00:18:09.780 --> 00:18:11.560
And that led us--

00:18:11.560 --> 00:18:14.730
in addition to a one-fold axis,
a two-fold access, a

00:18:14.730 --> 00:18:18.260
three-fold axis, a four-fold
axis, and a six-fold axis--

00:18:18.260 --> 00:18:22.440
let us combine reflection with
these axes to get symmetry

00:18:22.440 --> 00:18:26.080
combinations that we named
according to the symmetry

00:18:26.080 --> 00:18:29.130
elements which were present
in the final combination.

00:18:29.130 --> 00:18:34.990
We used two mirror planes if the
mirror planes that arose

00:18:34.990 --> 00:18:38.410
where independent.

00:18:38.410 --> 00:18:41.770
Independent in the sense that
the two-fold axis never turned

00:18:41.770 --> 00:18:42.750
one into another.

00:18:42.750 --> 00:18:45.750
And independent in the sense
that if we draw a

00:18:45.750 --> 00:18:50.970
representative motif, the way
those motifs were disposed

00:18:50.970 --> 00:18:53.900
about one mirror plane was
different from the way they

00:18:53.900 --> 00:18:56.730
were arranged about
the other one.

00:18:56.730 --> 00:19:00.830
For a four-fold axis, we could
add mirror planes.

00:19:00.830 --> 00:19:03.830
And they would have to be
at half the angle of the

00:19:03.830 --> 00:19:07.380
four-fold axis.

00:19:07.380 --> 00:19:09.450
And as we saw, it was
kind of a mouthful

00:19:09.450 --> 00:19:10.700
to call this 4MMMMMMMM.

00:19:13.110 --> 00:19:16.210
There were just two kinds of
mirror planes, so this one was

00:19:16.210 --> 00:19:18.240
called 4MM.

00:19:18.240 --> 00:19:23.300
6MM, analogously, was a six-fold
axis with mirror

00:19:23.300 --> 00:19:26.490
planes separated by 30 degrees,
half the throw of the

00:19:26.490 --> 00:19:28.400
six-fold axis.

00:19:28.400 --> 00:19:35.370
And the one that I left out is
3, not m m but 3M because a

00:19:35.370 --> 00:19:41.540
three-fold axis has
mirror planes

00:19:41.540 --> 00:19:43.750
separated by 60 degrees.

00:19:43.750 --> 00:19:49.190
And the same thing goes on at
each of these mirror planes,

00:19:49.190 --> 00:19:52.730
pair of objects hanging at one
end of the mirror plane, the

00:19:52.730 --> 00:19:54.730
other end is unadorned.

00:19:54.730 --> 00:19:56.180
So they all behave the same.

00:19:56.180 --> 00:19:58.060
There's only one kind
of mirror plane.

00:19:58.060 --> 00:20:01.530
The three-fold axis maps one
mirror plane into another, and

00:20:01.530 --> 00:20:03.360
so they have to be the same.

00:20:03.360 --> 00:20:11.130
So therefore, only one M
appears in the symbol.

00:20:11.130 --> 00:20:17.050
Independent of this, we had,
when we combined reflection or

00:20:17.050 --> 00:20:21.230
rotation with a lattice, found
that there were a very limited

00:20:21.230 --> 00:20:24.990
number of lattices in two
dimensions, the oblique

00:20:24.990 --> 00:20:33.560
lattice which had T1 not equal
to T2 and T1 inclined to T2 by

00:20:33.560 --> 00:20:36.690
some general angle.

00:20:36.690 --> 00:20:41.600
The next degree of
specialization was for a

00:20:41.600 --> 00:20:44.580
two-fold axis-- so either a
one-fold or a two-fold axis

00:20:44.580 --> 00:20:46.622
could fit in here.

00:20:46.622 --> 00:20:51.960
For a three-fold axis or a
six-fold axis, we had to have

00:20:51.960 --> 00:20:56.390
a lattice in which the two
translations were identical to

00:20:56.390 --> 00:21:01.230
one another, identical in
magnitude and identical in the

00:21:01.230 --> 00:21:05.060
way the atoms were ranged
relative to these

00:21:05.060 --> 00:21:06.300
translations.

00:21:06.300 --> 00:21:10.740
And the angle between
T1 over T2 had to be

00:21:10.740 --> 00:21:13.560
identically 120 degrees.

00:21:13.560 --> 00:21:17.920
And by convention, we take the
larger of two angles, 120

00:21:17.920 --> 00:21:21.806
rather than 60, to define
the inter axial angle.

00:21:21.806 --> 00:21:27.130
A four-fold axis required a net
that was exactly square,

00:21:27.130 --> 00:21:30.240
not approximately square
but exactly square.

00:21:30.240 --> 00:21:33.930
So T1 and T2 had to be identical
in magnitude.

00:21:33.930 --> 00:21:38.960
The angle between them had
to be exactly 90 degrees.

00:21:38.960 --> 00:21:40.300
And close is no cigar.

00:21:40.300 --> 00:21:43.700
It has to be exactly 90 degrees
because that angle is

00:21:43.700 --> 00:21:45.700
generated by symmetry.

00:21:45.700 --> 00:21:48.930
And then at the place in which
I'm gonna pick up today in

00:21:48.930 --> 00:21:53.975
just a moment is the case of a
mirror plane and reflection,

00:21:53.975 --> 00:21:57.970
we saw depending on how we
arranged the translations

00:21:57.970 --> 00:22:02.090
relative to the reflection
plane, could give us either a

00:22:02.090 --> 00:22:05.290
lattice in the shape
of a rectangle--

00:22:05.290 --> 00:22:11.480
and here T1 and T2 made an angle
of exactly 90 degrees.

00:22:11.480 --> 00:22:15.210
But the magnitude of T1 could be
anything it liked relative

00:22:15.210 --> 00:22:20.400
to the magnitude of T2, and then
a double cell, which had

00:22:20.400 --> 00:22:24.140
the shape of a diamond.

00:22:24.140 --> 00:22:28.820
But it was operationally much
to our advantage to pick a

00:22:28.820 --> 00:22:33.200
double cell which had
a right angle in it.

00:22:33.200 --> 00:22:36.940
And the reason for that was that
it is a nightmare to do

00:22:36.940 --> 00:22:40.750
calculations of inter-atomic
distances and angles or angles

00:22:40.750 --> 00:22:44.040
between faces in an
oblique system.

00:22:44.040 --> 00:22:47.980
The right angle makes these
calculations very simple.

00:22:47.980 --> 00:22:51.270
And the fact that this cell
tells you twice as much of the

00:22:51.270 --> 00:22:55.330
area as you really need
to know about is a

00:22:55.330 --> 00:22:56.650
small price to pay.

00:22:56.650 --> 00:22:59.810
So this is the rectangular
net, as

00:22:59.810 --> 00:23:01.550
we'll call it in words.

00:23:04.830 --> 00:23:06.480
And this is one that
we'll call the

00:23:06.480 --> 00:23:07.730
centered rectangular net.

00:23:14.690 --> 00:23:15.170
OK.

00:23:15.170 --> 00:23:17.660
So let me pause here and suck
in air and see if there are

00:23:17.660 --> 00:23:19.766
any questions.

00:23:19.766 --> 00:23:21.590
This is where we left off.

00:23:21.590 --> 00:23:24.500
And now having everything spread
out on the board, we're

00:23:24.500 --> 00:23:26.320
going to start to make
combinations and

00:23:26.320 --> 00:23:27.310
continue that process.

00:23:27.310 --> 00:23:28.090
Yes, sir.

00:23:28.090 --> 00:23:29.743
AUDIENCE: So the centered
rectangular has the same exact

00:23:29.743 --> 00:23:31.961
[? intercept ?] as the
rectangular but the only thing

00:23:31.961 --> 00:23:34.180
you're doing is you're deriving
it based on symmetry

00:23:34.180 --> 00:23:36.645
that you're using like a diamond
kind of thing to get

00:23:36.645 --> 00:23:37.138
the center one?

00:23:37.138 --> 00:23:37.640
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:23:37.640 --> 00:23:41.760
So all these arose when we did
it slowly and systematically.

00:23:41.760 --> 00:23:45.930
We said let's let this be the
location of the mirror plane.

00:23:45.930 --> 00:23:49.210
What happens if we combine
it with a translation?

00:23:49.210 --> 00:23:51.820
We can take one lattice point
on the mirror plane since

00:23:51.820 --> 00:23:53.740
there's no unique
lattice point.

00:23:53.740 --> 00:23:55.530
And then the mirror plane
is gonna reflect

00:23:55.530 --> 00:23:57.710
this over to here.

00:23:57.710 --> 00:23:59.340
So here's a first translation.

00:23:59.340 --> 00:24:02.170
I've got a second non-colinear
translation.

00:24:02.170 --> 00:24:03.420
Wham-o.

00:24:03.420 --> 00:24:04.530
Instant lattice.

00:24:04.530 --> 00:24:09.720
So what I'm doing is taking this
diamond shape and I am

00:24:09.720 --> 00:24:13.530
taking one translation here--
let's put some labels on this.

00:24:13.530 --> 00:24:16.870
Let's call this T1
and this T2.

00:24:16.870 --> 00:24:21.930
So this translation here, call
it T1 prime, is my original

00:24:21.930 --> 00:24:24.490
translation T1 plus T2.

00:24:24.490 --> 00:24:30.778
In this translation, T2 is
the negative of the--

00:24:30.778 --> 00:24:31.004
Yeah.

00:24:31.004 --> 00:24:34.660
It's gonna be minus
T1 plus T2.

00:24:34.660 --> 00:24:37.130
So I've taken linear
combinations of the two

00:24:37.130 --> 00:24:38.950
vectors of the diamond-shaped
cell.

00:24:41.590 --> 00:24:46.870
And again, this is contrary to
the rules we have that say

00:24:46.870 --> 00:24:48.980
pick the shortest two
translations.

00:24:48.980 --> 00:24:50.010
Why?

00:24:50.010 --> 00:24:52.295
The final larger area of
volume then you need.

00:24:52.295 --> 00:24:56.990
And the answer to that is
occasionally the provision of

00:24:56.990 --> 00:25:00.970
a coordinate system, which is
far easier to work in, is a

00:25:00.970 --> 00:25:04.375
small price to pay for
that redundancy.

00:25:04.375 --> 00:25:04.800
OK.

00:25:04.800 --> 00:25:06.770
And then the primitive
rectangular net, just to

00:25:06.770 --> 00:25:09.855
remind you again, we said is
there any case in which this

00:25:09.855 --> 00:25:11.100
is not true?

00:25:11.100 --> 00:25:15.380
And that case was if you take
T1 exactly perpendicular to

00:25:15.380 --> 00:25:19.200
the mirror plane and then you
define only a lattice row.

00:25:19.200 --> 00:25:22.110
So that gives you a second
choice for T2.

00:25:22.110 --> 00:25:24.960
You can't pick it anywhere you
like, otherwise it gets

00:25:24.960 --> 00:25:27.970
reflected across just as in the
first case, and you have

00:25:27.970 --> 00:25:31.800
two translations that
are not compatible.

00:25:31.800 --> 00:25:35.850
And the only way that they are
compatible is that if you make

00:25:35.850 --> 00:25:38.870
the translation T1 straddle
the mirror plane.

00:25:38.870 --> 00:25:40.810
And that's what we've
already got up here.

00:25:40.810 --> 00:25:42.870
So that's how we got the
rectangular net.

00:25:42.870 --> 00:25:46.320
We could get a second distinct
sort of lattice only if this

00:25:46.320 --> 00:25:49.460
translation was exactly in the
plane of the mirror line.

00:25:49.460 --> 00:25:49.880
Yes, sir.

00:25:49.880 --> 00:25:53.039
AUDIENCE: But the number and
kind of symmetry elements are

00:25:53.039 --> 00:25:54.740
the same for both, right?

00:25:54.740 --> 00:25:56.684
PROFESSOR: Exactly.

00:25:56.684 --> 00:25:58.640
AUDIENCE: Uh, so--

00:25:58.640 --> 00:26:01.670
PROFESSOR: So there's a curious
sort of duality here.

00:26:01.670 --> 00:26:06.610
Here in the case of a hexagonal
net, this is just a

00:26:06.610 --> 00:26:10.030
lattice of a very specialized
shape.

00:26:10.030 --> 00:26:12.790
And does that have a six-fold
axis in it?

00:26:12.790 --> 00:26:14.870
No, not unless I decide
to put one in.

00:26:14.870 --> 00:26:17.660
I could put in a three-fold
axis, alternatively.

00:26:17.660 --> 00:26:20.700
So here, I have one lattice that
can accept two different

00:26:20.700 --> 00:26:21.900
kinds of symmetry.

00:26:21.900 --> 00:26:23.950
Here I've got the reverse
situation.

00:26:23.950 --> 00:26:27.500
I have two distinct kind of
lattices, both of which are

00:26:27.500 --> 00:26:31.860
happy and content with the
same symmetry on them.

00:26:31.860 --> 00:26:35.560
So there's going to be a far
greater number of combinations

00:26:35.560 --> 00:26:39.180
of lattice with symmetry than
simply a one-to-one

00:26:39.180 --> 00:26:43.600
correspondence between lattice
types and point group types.

00:26:49.040 --> 00:26:49.440
OK.

00:26:49.440 --> 00:26:50.690
Any other questions?

00:26:53.120 --> 00:26:58.460
All right so let me now shift
down to low gear and remind

00:26:58.460 --> 00:27:03.930
you of one thing that
we did last time.

00:27:03.930 --> 00:27:14.060
We asked what happens if I can
combine a rotation operation,

00:27:14.060 --> 00:27:18.690
a alpha, with a translation?

00:27:18.690 --> 00:27:21.510
Call this T1.

00:27:21.510 --> 00:27:25.900
Sounds like something I already
did in showing that

00:27:25.900 --> 00:27:30.490
the values of alpha are
restricted to values.

00:27:30.490 --> 00:27:34.480
But what I'm going to do now is
use something that looks as

00:27:34.480 --> 00:27:38.220
though it's a similar starting
point to arrive at a different

00:27:38.220 --> 00:27:41.270
result that we saw last time.

00:27:41.270 --> 00:27:47.760
I'm going to deliberately look
at a line that is alpha over 2

00:27:47.760 --> 00:27:52.410
on one side of the perpendicular
to T1.

00:27:52.410 --> 00:27:58.730
And then the operation of the a
alpha is going to take this

00:27:58.730 --> 00:28:01.930
translation with a lattice point
of necessity at the end

00:28:01.930 --> 00:28:06.530
of it, and it's going to move it
over to here, alpha over 2,

00:28:06.530 --> 00:28:10.540
on the other side of the
translation of the

00:28:10.540 --> 00:28:12.470
perpendicular.

00:28:12.470 --> 00:28:15.850
Then I'm going to pick this up
with the translation T1 and

00:28:15.850 --> 00:28:21.050
move it and everything along
it to a location like this.

00:28:21.050 --> 00:28:28.280
And my question now is, what
is a alpha followed by the

00:28:28.280 --> 00:28:31.805
translation T1?

00:28:31.805 --> 00:28:34.540
The handedness of the objects
have not changed.

00:28:34.540 --> 00:28:35.900
So this has to be either

00:28:35.900 --> 00:28:39.530
translation or another rotation.

00:28:39.530 --> 00:28:43.510
And what we can very quickly
show is if upon dropping a

00:28:43.510 --> 00:28:48.050
perpendicular down to the
original translation, these

00:28:48.050 --> 00:28:49.310
lines are parallel.

00:28:49.310 --> 00:28:50.800
This line cuts across it.

00:28:50.800 --> 00:28:54.470
So this angle is alpha over 2.

00:28:54.470 --> 00:28:58.730
And this line is inclined
to the perpendicular

00:28:58.730 --> 00:29:00.140
by alpha over 2.

00:29:00.140 --> 00:29:05.580
So this angle in here is
also alpha over 2.

00:29:05.580 --> 00:29:11.900
So the answer is that if I
rotate from one location to

00:29:11.900 --> 00:29:16.420
another by rotation alpha and
then pick up that motif or the

00:29:16.420 --> 00:29:22.710
entire space and translate it by
the original translation T1

00:29:22.710 --> 00:29:26.010
to get a third one-- this is
number 1, right-handed, say,

00:29:26.010 --> 00:29:28.040
number 2, right-handed.

00:29:28.040 --> 00:29:29.150
This is number 3.

00:29:29.150 --> 00:29:30.470
Stays right-handed.

00:29:30.470 --> 00:29:32.750
Has to be related
by a rotation.

00:29:32.750 --> 00:29:37.540
And we next ask, what point is
the point about which the

00:29:37.540 --> 00:29:39.230
rotation occurs?

00:29:39.230 --> 00:29:40.110
Then we used--

00:29:40.110 --> 00:29:44.240
what at the time seemed like
a trivial observation--

00:29:44.240 --> 00:29:47.830
that a rotation axis in space
or a rotation point in two

00:29:47.830 --> 00:29:51.080
dimensions is the locus
that is left

00:29:51.080 --> 00:29:55.500
unmoved by the rotation.

00:29:55.500 --> 00:30:00.460
So if rotating from here and
translating over to here is

00:30:00.460 --> 00:30:03.770
equivalent to a rotation and if
the locus of the rotation

00:30:03.770 --> 00:30:08.530
has to be the point that's
left on moved, bingo.

00:30:08.530 --> 00:30:11.370
That's where the rotation
occurs.

00:30:11.370 --> 00:30:14.260
And it's through the same angle,
so we can label this an

00:30:14.260 --> 00:30:16.870
operation b alpha.

00:30:16.870 --> 00:30:21.050
And we know exactly where
that point is gonna be.

00:30:21.050 --> 00:30:24.080
It's gonna be along the
perpendicular bisector of the

00:30:24.080 --> 00:30:25.300
original translation.

00:30:25.300 --> 00:30:30.180
And it's gonna be up a distance
x which is T over 2

00:30:30.180 --> 00:30:33.185
times the cotangent
of alpha over 2.

00:30:33.185 --> 00:30:38.490
So now we've got another, what
I call, combination theorems.

00:30:38.490 --> 00:30:42.260
And again, this is nothing
more than knowing how to

00:30:42.260 --> 00:30:46.490
complete the product of two
operations in establishing the

00:30:46.490 --> 00:30:48.130
group multiplication table.

00:30:48.130 --> 00:30:51.970
so let me write it down in the
form of a combination theorem.

00:30:51.970 --> 00:30:59.060
This says that a alpha followed
by a translation is

00:30:59.060 --> 00:31:01.570
another rotation--

00:31:01.570 --> 00:31:04.190
in the same sense, both counter

00:31:04.190 --> 00:31:06.550
clockwise in this example--

00:31:06.550 --> 00:31:10.280
another rotation b alpha in the
same sense about a point

00:31:10.280 --> 00:31:15.550
that is always T over 2 times
the cotangent of alpha over 2

00:31:15.550 --> 00:31:18.310
along the perpendicular
bisector.

00:31:18.310 --> 00:31:20.870
So that's how you would go about
making an entry in the

00:31:20.870 --> 00:31:24.050
group multiplication table.

00:31:24.050 --> 00:31:24.260
Sorry.

00:31:24.260 --> 00:31:24.890
I put you off.

00:31:24.890 --> 00:31:25.316
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:31:25.316 --> 00:31:27.840
Can you just, like, I just
want to see what you did

00:31:27.840 --> 00:31:30.830
actually to the motif
in that drawing.

00:31:30.830 --> 00:31:31.310
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:31:31.310 --> 00:31:35.520
Rather than taking an
abstraction, an arbitrary line

00:31:35.520 --> 00:31:40.210
that is at alpha over 2, I put
a motif in the space that

00:31:40.210 --> 00:31:44.240
doesn't necessarily hang on this
particular locus that I

00:31:44.240 --> 00:31:45.550
drew for reference.

00:31:45.550 --> 00:31:49.650
And the rotation through alpha
would move it to here.

00:31:49.650 --> 00:31:51.600
It's lagging behind
this first line.

00:31:51.600 --> 00:31:54.550
It lagged behind the second
one by the same amount.

00:31:54.550 --> 00:31:57.850
Then I pick it up and I move it
by the same translation and

00:31:57.850 --> 00:32:02.780
that slides it over here, still
canted over to the left.

00:32:02.780 --> 00:32:06.260
And now what I claim is that I
get from the first one to the

00:32:06.260 --> 00:32:07.170
third one--

00:32:07.170 --> 00:32:09.740
and actually should have
raised your hand on a

00:32:09.740 --> 00:32:10.470
different matter.

00:32:10.470 --> 00:32:12.540
This is out in front
of the translation.

00:32:12.540 --> 00:32:15.380
So number 3 should sit here,
also to the right to the

00:32:15.380 --> 00:32:16.720
translation.

00:32:16.720 --> 00:32:19.590
And the way I get from 1
to 3 in one shot is by

00:32:19.590 --> 00:32:20.919
rotating alpha b.

00:32:23.913 --> 00:32:26.408
OK.

00:32:26.408 --> 00:32:31.840
Now, a cautionary note just so
you do not use your new power

00:32:31.840 --> 00:32:33.330
recklessly.

00:32:33.330 --> 00:32:47.710
Let me emphasize that this is
an escalation in operations,

00:32:47.710 --> 00:32:49.183
not in symmetry elements.

00:32:59.260 --> 00:33:04.990
And the reason for that is
that a rotation axis, in

00:33:04.990 --> 00:33:08.190
general, contains a number
of different rotations.

00:33:08.190 --> 00:33:12.840
An n-fold axis has n different
rotation operations implied in

00:33:12.840 --> 00:33:15.760
it, including the identity
operation of

00:33:15.760 --> 00:33:17.850
rotating 360 degrees.

00:33:17.850 --> 00:33:21.460
So if I say I'm gonna drop a
four-fold access in a lattice,

00:33:21.460 --> 00:33:24.570
what I'm doing is dropping into
the lattice a 90 degree

00:33:24.570 --> 00:33:27.430
rotation, a 180 degree
rotation, and

00:33:27.430 --> 00:33:30.180
a 270 degree rotation.

00:33:30.180 --> 00:33:35.500
And the location of the new
operations depends on alpha.

00:33:35.500 --> 00:33:38.050
So these new operations
are not gonna pop

00:33:38.050 --> 00:33:39.560
up at the same location.

00:33:39.560 --> 00:33:43.660
They're gonna be sprinkled
over different locations.

00:33:43.660 --> 00:33:46.740
So as an abstraction, that may
be hard to appreciate.

00:33:46.740 --> 00:33:49.960
But we're going to straight
away derive a

00:33:49.960 --> 00:33:52.560
couple of more additions.

00:33:52.560 --> 00:33:56.320
And then when we see what
happens upon adding a rotation

00:33:56.320 --> 00:34:00.570
axis to a lattice in a couple of
nontrivial cases, I'll just

00:34:00.570 --> 00:34:03.710
summarize the results and assume
that you'll be able to

00:34:03.710 --> 00:34:06.450
derive them on your own.

00:34:06.450 --> 00:34:09.120
The last time we had got around
to doing just one of

00:34:09.120 --> 00:34:11.460
these combinations.

00:34:11.460 --> 00:34:16.730
And we ask what happens when you
combine with a translation

00:34:16.730 --> 00:34:20.290
a rotation operation a pi.

00:34:20.290 --> 00:34:24.760
So we'll take some motif that
sets up here, right-handed,

00:34:24.760 --> 00:34:29.960
rotate it by 180 degrees to
get a second one, and then

00:34:29.960 --> 00:34:35.020
pick that up and translate it by
T. So I'll get a third one

00:34:35.020 --> 00:34:39.650
sitting down like this of
the same handedness.

00:34:39.650 --> 00:34:41.750
And the question now is
how do I get from

00:34:41.750 --> 00:34:43.449
1 to number 3 directly?

00:34:43.449 --> 00:34:45.020
Well, let's use our theorem.

00:34:45.020 --> 00:34:48.010
Our theorem says we should
go a distance x along the

00:34:48.010 --> 00:34:52.989
perpendicular bisector, which
is half the magnitude of T

00:34:52.989 --> 00:34:57.310
times the cotangent
of pi over 2.

00:34:57.310 --> 00:35:00.120
The cotangent of pi
over 2 is zero.

00:35:00.120 --> 00:35:01.760
So we go up a distance x.

00:35:01.760 --> 00:35:04.860
That's equal to 0, all in the
perpendicular bisector, which

00:35:04.860 --> 00:35:06.680
means we stay put.

00:35:06.680 --> 00:35:08.860
And--

00:35:08.860 --> 00:35:13.060
in this class, there is always
truth in advertising.

00:35:13.060 --> 00:35:18.580
Around this locus here is a
rotation operation b pi, which

00:35:18.580 --> 00:35:22.820
takes the first one into
the third one.

00:35:22.820 --> 00:35:25.720
OK.

00:35:25.720 --> 00:35:30.450
And now, lickety split, I will
derive again-- and I apologize

00:35:30.450 --> 00:35:33.500
for going fast because I
did do it last time.

00:35:33.500 --> 00:35:37.730
Let's ask what happens when we
combine a two-fold axis with a

00:35:37.730 --> 00:35:40.160
parallelogram net?

00:35:40.160 --> 00:35:44.030
So we're taking a two-fold axis
plus a parallelogram net.

00:35:47.020 --> 00:35:49.070
In this two dimensional
lattice there are two

00:35:49.070 --> 00:35:54.880
translations, T1 and T2, of
arbitrary magnitude with some

00:35:54.880 --> 00:35:56.960
angle between them
that's arbitrary.

00:35:56.960 --> 00:36:01.440
And to this lattice point,
I'll add a two-fold axis.

00:36:01.440 --> 00:36:06.880
A two-fold axis involves the
presence of two operations,

00:36:06.880 --> 00:36:10.490
the identity operation, and that
we can forget about, and

00:36:10.490 --> 00:36:14.520
then there's the
operation a pi.

00:36:14.520 --> 00:36:19.250
By combine a pi with T1, I'll
get an operation b pi that

00:36:19.250 --> 00:36:20.910
sits at the midpoint of T1.

00:36:20.910 --> 00:36:28.340
If I combine a pi with T2, we
get an operation c pi at the

00:36:28.340 --> 00:36:29.900
midpoint of T2.

00:36:29.900 --> 00:36:37.540
If I combine a pi with T1 plus
T2, I'll get another operation

00:36:37.540 --> 00:36:40.680
d pi at the center
of the cell.

00:36:40.680 --> 00:36:44.540
And we don't have to ask what
happens when we go three

00:36:44.540 --> 00:36:46.160
translations over.

00:36:46.160 --> 00:36:49.730
There's gonna be another
operation of 180 degree

00:36:49.730 --> 00:36:51.340
rotation on that translation.

00:36:51.340 --> 00:36:55.420
But we really only need bother
about what goes on on the

00:36:55.420 --> 00:36:58.720
edges and in the interior of
one unit cell, because

00:36:58.720 --> 00:37:02.340
whatever's there has to be
repeated by translation.

00:37:02.340 --> 00:37:15.270
So, in making these additions,
we need consider only

00:37:15.270 --> 00:37:16.740
independent translations--

00:37:16.740 --> 00:37:19.110
that is, not related
to one another by

00:37:19.110 --> 00:37:20.660
the rotational symmetry--

00:37:20.660 --> 00:37:28.050
independent translations
that terminate

00:37:28.050 --> 00:37:29.300
within the unit cell.

00:37:40.910 --> 00:37:45.860
And that means for the addition
of a two-fold axis, I

00:37:45.860 --> 00:37:48.570
need do only what I have,
in fact, just done.

00:37:48.570 --> 00:37:57.850
I want to consider a pi with
T1, T2, and T1 plus T2.

00:38:02.180 --> 00:38:07.010
If I have the operation a pi
or b pi or c pi or d pi at

00:38:07.010 --> 00:38:15.720
these four locations, that is
all I need have present to say

00:38:15.720 --> 00:38:19.250
that I have, in addition to the
two-fold axis that I added

00:38:19.250 --> 00:38:23.390
to the lattice point, a two-fold
axis halfway along

00:38:23.390 --> 00:38:28.230
T1, a two-fold access halfway
along T2, and another one

00:38:28.230 --> 00:38:30.680
smack in the middle
of the cell.

00:38:30.680 --> 00:38:32.140
These are lattice points.

00:38:32.140 --> 00:38:36.050
So those axes have to be
repeated by translations, this

00:38:36.050 --> 00:38:40.560
one from here to here, this one
from here, this one from

00:38:40.560 --> 00:38:41.600
here to here.

00:38:41.600 --> 00:38:45.240
So I'll have two-fold axes in
the middle of all of the edges

00:38:45.240 --> 00:38:51.150
of the cell plus this fourth
one right in the middle.

00:38:51.150 --> 00:38:56.610
So this is an example of a two
dimensional space group.

00:38:56.610 --> 00:39:01.470
It's a symmetry that acts
on all of space.

00:39:01.470 --> 00:39:10.400
And the names that we will give
to these combinations is

00:39:10.400 --> 00:39:14.820
a symbol for the symmetry
element that we added, in this

00:39:14.820 --> 00:39:16.930
case a two-fold axis.

00:39:16.930 --> 00:39:21.480
And then we'll specify the
nature of the lattice to which

00:39:21.480 --> 00:39:22.630
we've added it.

00:39:22.630 --> 00:39:25.930
And all that I have to say is
that the lattice is primitive

00:39:25.930 --> 00:39:30.200
because you're all aware at
this point that a two-fold

00:39:30.200 --> 00:39:33.540
axis requires only
a primitive, a

00:39:33.540 --> 00:39:34.990
parallelogram net.

00:39:34.990 --> 00:39:37.770
The only place we'll need a
special symbol is when we add

00:39:37.770 --> 00:39:40.610
a mirror plane to either the
rectangular net or the

00:39:40.610 --> 00:39:41.910
centered rectangular net.

00:39:41.910 --> 00:39:45.450
And then we'll have to specify
which type of lattice of that

00:39:45.450 --> 00:39:48.023
shape, primitive or centered,
we're dealing with.

00:39:48.023 --> 00:39:48.790
Yes, sir.

00:39:48.790 --> 00:39:50.511
AUDIENCE: So all you did with
that derivation there is prove

00:39:50.511 --> 00:39:52.115
that you don't have
to worry about any

00:39:52.115 --> 00:39:54.039
rotations outside of that?

00:39:54.039 --> 00:39:54.520
PROFESSOR: That's correct.

00:39:54.520 --> 00:39:55.482
AUDIENCE: That's correct?

00:39:55.482 --> 00:39:57.410
PROFESSOR: Yep.

00:39:57.410 --> 00:39:59.640
Which is very fortunate 'cause
there's an infinite number

00:39:59.640 --> 00:40:02.730
lurking outside the boundaries
of the cell.

00:40:02.730 --> 00:40:05.300
I'll show you another
general truth.

00:40:05.300 --> 00:40:07.650
What does a pattern look like?

00:40:07.650 --> 00:40:12.780
The pattern looks exactly like
the pattern of a two-fold axis

00:40:12.780 --> 00:40:16.530
with that pattern of motifs hung
at every lattice point.

00:40:23.780 --> 00:40:29.250
These new two-fold axes don't
do any further repetition of

00:40:29.250 --> 00:40:31.610
the motifs.

00:40:31.610 --> 00:40:34.040
They don't do any repetition
of the motif.

00:40:34.040 --> 00:40:38.770
They just express relation
between things that you get

00:40:38.770 --> 00:40:41.820
when you take this pair and
then repeat it by the

00:40:41.820 --> 00:40:43.250
translations.

00:40:43.250 --> 00:40:46.500
So this two-fold access, for
example, relates this to this.

00:40:46.500 --> 00:40:49.460
This two-fold axis relates this
one to this one, and this

00:40:49.460 --> 00:40:51.130
one to this one, and so on.

00:40:51.130 --> 00:40:54.280
They're just relations that
exist between the things that

00:40:54.280 --> 00:40:57.260
you get when you add the pattern
of a two-fold axis to

00:40:57.260 --> 00:40:59.090
a lattice point.

00:40:59.090 --> 00:41:02.420
So another generalization of
what we're doing here that

00:41:02.420 --> 00:41:17.100
turns out to be valid, the
pattern of motifs for a

00:41:17.100 --> 00:41:43.460
particular plane group is
nothing more than the pattern

00:41:43.460 --> 00:41:44.760
of the symmetry element--

00:41:51.540 --> 00:41:55.670
symmetry element or symmetry
elements, sometimes we'll be

00:41:55.670 --> 00:41:56.920
adding more than one--

00:42:08.890 --> 00:42:12.330
that we've added to
a lattice point.

00:42:21.090 --> 00:42:25.330
So in other words, if we take
2MM and drop that into a

00:42:25.330 --> 00:42:27.700
rectangular lattice, the pattern
is simply gonna be

00:42:27.700 --> 00:42:33.400
these four atoms related by 2MM
hung at every corner of

00:42:33.400 --> 00:42:34.385
the lattice.

00:42:34.385 --> 00:42:37.700
If you add it to a centered
lattice, these would be hung

00:42:37.700 --> 00:42:39.890
at every corner of the lattice,
and also at the

00:42:39.890 --> 00:42:41.330
centered lattice point.

00:42:41.330 --> 00:42:42.790
So it's that simple.

00:42:42.790 --> 00:42:45.490
If you look at some of these
high symmetry space groups or

00:42:45.490 --> 00:42:48.050
plane groups, wow, there's
symmetry all over the place.

00:42:48.050 --> 00:42:49.960
You say, how can I draw
a pattern for that?

00:42:49.960 --> 00:42:50.550
Easy.

00:42:50.550 --> 00:42:53.060
Just do what the point group
does and drop it in at the

00:42:53.060 --> 00:42:55.300
lattice points.

00:42:55.300 --> 00:42:59.530
So that turns out to be a
universal feature of all space

00:42:59.530 --> 00:43:00.780
groups and plane groups.

00:43:03.187 --> 00:43:03.670
OK.

00:43:03.670 --> 00:43:05.320
Somebody had a question over
here and I cut you off.

00:43:05.320 --> 00:43:05.750
Yeah.

