On that two [INAUDIBLE] diagram,
wouldn't you want to

00:43:08.871 --> 00:43:11.642
use four of those because you
said it was-- you don't

00:43:11.642 --> 00:43:14.255
concern ones that are-- you're
only concerned independent

00:43:14.255 --> 00:43:15.690
ones, the ones you
can't get by--

00:43:15.690 --> 00:43:17.090
PROFESSOR: You're absolutely
right.

00:43:17.090 --> 00:43:19.070
And let's look at this
pattern again.

00:43:19.070 --> 00:43:21.610
Here are a pair that are
hanging close to

00:43:21.610 --> 00:43:23.680
this two-fold axis.

00:43:23.680 --> 00:43:26.910
Here's a pair hanging close
to the two-fold axis, very

00:43:26.910 --> 00:43:30.520
different arrangement, different
arrangement relative

00:43:30.520 --> 00:43:32.780
to this two-fold axis, different
arrangements

00:43:32.780 --> 00:43:34.260
relative to this
two-fold axis.

00:43:34.260 --> 00:43:36.660
So what we're saying is-- and
this is the way, in fact, we

00:43:36.660 --> 00:43:37.680
derive them--

00:43:37.680 --> 00:43:41.640
that these four two-fold
axes are all distinct.

00:43:41.640 --> 00:43:46.210
But the ones that are along the
edges are just related by

00:43:46.210 --> 00:43:47.800
translation.

00:43:47.800 --> 00:43:49.420
So why do I have
to put them in?

00:43:49.420 --> 00:43:52.240
AUDIENCE: You just put them in
to just show the symmetry?

00:43:52.240 --> 00:43:52.710
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:43:52.710 --> 00:43:53.490
Exactly.

00:43:53.490 --> 00:43:57.080
Exactly. 'Cause if I say this
is a lattice and I have

00:43:57.080 --> 00:44:03.900
two-fold axes here, that's an
incomplete representation

00:44:03.900 --> 00:44:05.980
because if these are
