00:46:06.490 --> 00:46:08.900
thing and a little easier
to deal with.

00:46:08.900 --> 00:46:11.860
And then the operation a2 pi,
which is the same as the

00:46:11.860 --> 00:46:13.020
identity operation.

00:46:13.020 --> 00:46:14.950
And that's dull and
uninteresting, so we won't

00:46:14.950 --> 00:46:17.580
consider that addition.

00:46:17.580 --> 00:46:22.820
We've already done this,
a pi, in deriving P2.

00:46:22.820 --> 00:46:24.810
And that's the nice thing
about this derivation.

00:46:24.810 --> 00:46:28.400
It's gonna snowball because as
the symmetry gets higher,

00:46:28.400 --> 00:46:32.220
we've already done the work for
the subgroup that contains

00:46:32.220 --> 00:46:34.955
the elements that are present
in the higher symmetry.

00:46:34.955 --> 00:46:39.550
So we'll get an operation
a pi over a pi here.

00:46:39.550 --> 00:46:42.010
We'll get an operation
a pi here.

00:46:42.010 --> 00:46:45.950
And if we take the diagonal
translation, T1 plus T2, I'll

00:46:45.950 --> 00:46:47.600
get the operation a pi here.

00:46:47.600 --> 00:46:52.260
Or I should probably call them
a pi, b pi, and c pi to

00:46:52.260 --> 00:46:58.050
indicate that these are
different two-fold axes.

00:46:58.050 --> 00:46:58.510
OK.

00:46:58.510 --> 00:47:03.580
Let me emphasize again that this
theorem that we have is a

00:47:03.580 --> 00:47:06.330
theorem in individual
operations and

00:47:06.330 --> 00:47:07.760
not symmetry elements.

00:47:07.760 --> 00:47:10.670
If I say a four-fold axis is
present, it means that all of

00:47:10.670 --> 00:47:13.560
these operations exist
about that locus.

00:47:13.560 --> 00:47:18.260
I cannot say that a four-fold
axis sits here.

00:47:18.260 --> 00:47:20.550
I cannot say a four-fold
axis sits here.

00:47:20.550 --> 00:47:24.740
I'm gonna have to take each of
these combinations in turn and

00:47:24.740 --> 00:47:29.250
then step back and see what
operations exist about the

00:47:29.250 --> 00:47:31.720
various loci within the cell.

00:47:31.720 --> 00:47:34.890
So the one that's really
different is the combination

00:47:34.890 --> 00:47:40.465
of a translation T with the
operation a pi over 2.

00:47:42.980 --> 00:47:52.300
And my theorem says if I put in
a motif and rotate it by 90

00:47:52.300 --> 00:47:53.550
degrees to here--

00:47:53.550 --> 00:47:56.770
so this is number 1 and
this is number 2--

00:47:56.770 --> 00:48:02.780
and then translate it to a
location that's related to the

00:48:02.780 --> 00:48:05.010
first by symmetry--

00:48:05.010 --> 00:48:08.030
by translation to
get number 3--

00:48:08.030 --> 00:48:15.240
they will be related by an
operation b pi over 2 that

00:48:15.240 --> 00:48:19.020
sits up along the perpendicular
bisector by an

00:48:19.020 --> 00:48:25.100
amount x, which is T over 2
times the cotangent of alpha

00:48:25.100 --> 00:48:36.483
over 2, T over 2 times the
cotangent of 1/2 of pi over 2,

00:48:36.483 --> 00:48:37.780
45 degrees.

00:48:37.780 --> 00:48:43.660
The cotangent of 45 degrees is
unity because the two edges of

00:48:43.660 --> 00:48:46.220
the triangle are equal
in length.

00:48:46.220 --> 00:48:50.860
So this says I should go up
along the perpendicular

00:48:50.860 --> 00:48:54.760
bisector by an amount that is
half the length of the cell.

00:48:57.810 --> 00:49:01.410
And that puts me right in
the middle of the cell.

00:49:01.410 --> 00:49:08.330
So the operation b pi over 2
sits not at the edge of the

00:49:08.330 --> 00:49:12.290
cell, but at the center
of the cell.

00:49:12.290 --> 00:49:17.660
And that, I think you will
agree, even in this hastily

00:49:17.660 --> 00:49:21.950
sketched diagram, is the way
number 1 is related directly

00:49:21.950 --> 00:49:23.860
to number 3 in one shot.

00:49:26.686 --> 00:49:29.970
Now I could do it on the
cheap from here.

00:49:29.970 --> 00:49:33.260
But let's show that
we have first an

00:49:33.260 --> 00:49:35.340
operation a pi over 2.

00:49:35.340 --> 00:49:38.520
We've already got the
operation c pi.

00:49:38.520 --> 00:49:43.070
Let's now combine the operation
a minus pi over 2.

00:49:46.810 --> 00:49:54.480
And that says that for c minus
pi over 2, I would go up the

00:49:54.480 --> 00:49:58.270
perpendicular bisector a
distance T over 2 times the

00:49:58.270 --> 00:50:03.400
cotangent of minus
1/2 of pi over 2.

00:50:03.400 --> 00:50:08.010
And the cotangent of a negative
angle is minus that.

00:50:08.010 --> 00:50:11.520
So I go a distance minus
T over 2 along the

00:50:11.520 --> 00:50:13.710
perpendicular bisector.

00:50:13.710 --> 00:50:19.870
And what that is gonna do is to
bring me to the center of

00:50:19.870 --> 00:50:22.510
the cell that's directly
below.

00:50:22.510 --> 00:50:30.000
And this will be the rotation
c minus pi over 2.

00:50:30.000 --> 00:50:32.650
But everything has to be
translation equivalent at the

00:50:32.650 --> 00:50:38.460
interval T. So I can just move
this operation c minus pi over

00:50:38.460 --> 00:50:42.160
2 up to the center of
my original cell.

00:50:42.160 --> 00:50:45.780
So now I have at the center of
the cell all the operations of

00:50:45.780 --> 00:50:48.700
a four-fold axis.

00:50:48.700 --> 00:50:53.370
So a four-fold axis exists in
the middle of the cell.

00:50:53.370 --> 00:50:56.660
And let me write the
results in here.

00:50:56.660 --> 00:50:59.420
I've now got all of the
operations of a four-fold axis

00:50:59.420 --> 00:51:00.540
sitting here.

00:51:00.540 --> 00:51:03.030
I've got all the operations
of a two-fold axis

00:51:03.030 --> 00:51:04.430
sitting here and here.

00:51:04.430 --> 00:51:08.650
So this is the final result,
if I translate the two-fold

00:51:08.650 --> 00:51:10.950
axes over to the other
edges of the cell.

00:51:17.410 --> 00:51:18.846
AUDIENCE: What is that angle
[? by the d project? ?]

00:51:18.846 --> 00:51:21.080
That should be 90 degrees?

00:51:21.080 --> 00:51:22.410
PROFESSOR: That should
be 90 degrees,

00:51:22.410 --> 00:51:23.580
if I drew it carefully.

00:51:23.580 --> 00:51:25.090
Yeah.

00:51:25.090 --> 00:51:32.250
So let me give the final result
with a pattern in it.

00:51:32.250 --> 00:51:34.350
These are the two translations,
equal in length,

00:51:34.350 --> 00:51:37.800
four-fold here, four-fold
here, four-fold here.

00:51:37.800 --> 00:51:40.620
They are all the same
four-fold axis.

00:51:40.620 --> 00:51:43.180
Four-fold axis in the
middle of the cell.

00:51:43.180 --> 00:51:46.970
Two-fold axis in the middle
of the cell edges.

00:51:46.970 --> 00:51:51.780
And the pattern of objects is
the set of things that are

00:51:51.780 --> 00:51:56.330
rotated by 90 degrees that form
a square about the corner

00:51:56.330 --> 00:51:57.580
of the cell.

00:51:59.570 --> 00:52:00.960
Another one here.

00:52:00.960 --> 00:52:04.760
Another one that sits up here.

00:52:04.760 --> 00:52:08.000
And another one that
sits like this.

00:52:08.000 --> 00:52:11.060
Four of them on the corners
of the square.

00:52:11.060 --> 00:52:14.830
And that's all we're going
to get in this pattern.

00:52:14.830 --> 00:52:19.440
Again, it's just a pattern of a
four-fold axis that is hung

00:52:19.440 --> 00:52:23.970
at every lattice point
of the square net.

00:52:23.970 --> 00:52:34.010
And these other symmetry
elements that arise simply are

00:52:34.010 --> 00:52:37.360
things that relate to the
squares that are hanging at

00:52:37.360 --> 00:52:40.350
every corner of the
square cell.

00:52:47.820 --> 00:52:48.180
OK.

00:52:48.180 --> 00:52:51.970
So the square in the center of
the cell, for example, relates

00:52:51.970 --> 00:52:53.520
these four.

00:52:53.520 --> 00:52:55.030
And you can pick any other
four and they'd

00:52:55.030 --> 00:52:56.230
be related as well.

00:52:56.230 --> 00:52:58.780
The two-fold axis relates
this to this.

00:52:58.780 --> 00:53:02.490
This two-fold axis relates this
to this and this to this.

00:53:02.490 --> 00:53:06.910
So the pattern is just the
square produced by four

00:53:06.910 --> 00:53:09.620
stamped out at every corner
of the square net.

00:53:09.620 --> 00:53:10.870
And it's that simple.

00:53:14.400 --> 00:53:17.164
The name of this thing--

00:53:17.164 --> 00:53:18.080
what have we done?

00:53:18.080 --> 00:53:20.740
We've taken a four-fold
axis, we've put it

00:53:20.740 --> 00:53:22.390
in a primitive net.

00:53:22.390 --> 00:53:26.520
I don't have to tell you it's
squared because in your heart

00:53:26.520 --> 00:53:28.455
of hearts know that
that is what a

00:53:28.455 --> 00:53:30.480
four-fold axis requires.

00:53:30.480 --> 00:53:32.050
So this describes
completely the

00:53:32.050 --> 00:53:33.810
combinations that's been made.

00:53:33.810 --> 00:53:36.010
And this is a representative
pattern.

00:53:36.010 --> 00:53:38.680
A pattern of this sort is one
